Let's give a big warm welcome to Tajah Haley. Ms. Haley will be a Fellow in First Grade with Ms. Hoisington.

Hello! My name is Tajah Haley. I will be a Fellow this year working with Ms. Hoisington's First Grade class.

I am from Pittsburgh, PA. I earned a Bachelors in Early Childhood. I'm currently working on my Masters in Special Education and Early Childhood.

I am born and raised in Pittsburgh, PA. Yes, I am a Steelers fan! I love coffee, sweet tea, and playing with my new puppy, Finn!

I love dancing and having fun with my students! I'm so excited to be in such an amazing school with wonderful students, teachers, and families!

#AthensBulldogs

post_text:
Check out the progress below on the East Elementary building site. Superintendent Dr. Gibbs and board members Kim Goldsberry and Dave Hayden took an on-site tour today.

Below you can see a few photos from their visit today.
You will see a photo of the front wall. The openings will be windows. This is the cafeteria looking into the gymnasium. A picture of what looks like "adult legos," but are actually used to construct an underground water retention tank. There will be two sets of "adult legos" on site. They will collect rainwater and hold it to slowly release it into the city’s water system so that we are more environmentally friendly, as well as good neighbors. We are standing on what will be the entrance hallway, next to the gym wall. Another photo shows the gymnasium wall. The large opening will hold the retractable wall. The smaller set of doors will hold gym storage. You can see a photo of the office area and the main entrance into the building.

Be on the lookout for photos of the Morrison-Gordon Elementary coming in the near future.

#AthensBulldogs

post_text:
The Athens Girls Varsity Soccer team opened their season in a tough loss to the Logan Chiefs Friday night. Keeper Bean adds to her career total with an additional 17 saves. Athens Head Coach JT Schroer summed up the game; "We are proud that the bulldogs didn't give up and played hard all game. We played better in the second half and only gave up one goal."

Athens and Logan JV teams met at Joe Burrow Stadium on Saturday. Sophomore Annie Moulton and Freshman Kayla Hammonds each found the net to lead the team to 2-0 victory.

Having found their synchronicity, the Bulldogs hope to blend this learning in their next game against Miami Trace on Thursday at home.
#AthensBulldogs⚽️

We have many new faces joining our #AthensBulldogs staff this school year. 💚 Help us welcome Mrs. Modrzakowski!

Hi! My name is Mrs. Modrzakowski. Students like to call me Mrs. Mod. I have been teaching for 30 years. This year I will be teaching 4th grade Math and Science at East-West Elementary!

I have been married for 22 years to my wonderful husband, Malcolm. We have one son, John. He studies accounting at Hocking College. John is planning to transfer to OU and finish his business degree. We also have three dogs, Tucker, Peanut, and Blue.

My favorite part of my job is interacting with students and watching them grow and learn! I am very excited about being a Bulldog this year!!!

ACCS School Outreach will be distributing peanut butter, jelly, bread and produce, each Thursday, through July 30th, from 11:00 a.m. -1:00 p.m. in front of The Plains Elementary main entrance.

Due to COVID-19 safety guidelines, our distribution will look different this year.

✔️ We ask that families arrive no earlier than 10:50 am.
✔️ Please remain in your cars, forming a line in the parking lot.
✔️ As you arrive at the main entrance, we ask that only 2 people at a time approach the entrance, and only 1 person per vehicle.
✔️ There will be signage to direct you to keep physical distance from other participants.
✔️ We ask that you wear a mask, if possible.

Our team will work as fast as we can to keep the line moving so folks don't have to wait too long.

Thank you for keeping all of us safe! We look forward to seeing you!

#AthensBulldogs

post_text:
Five students from Athens Middle School participated in the State Science Day in May. The State Science Day was a virtual fair, and the students each submitted a video to be judged.

Students who entered included Emerson Crowl, Helen Liu, and Eli McCarthy (7th graders) and Joonwoo Park and Xinrui Han (8th graders).

Emerson Crowl achieved a superior rating, and was also awarded the Ohio Environmental Health Association Award for his project on composting, “The Biodegradation Race.” Joonwoo Park also achieved a superior rating for his project entitled “Utilizing Food Waste to Promote Algae Biofuel Production,” and he was awarded the Governor’s Award for Excellence in Environmental Protection Research, as well as the Milt Austin Aquatic Science Award.

Congratulations to all who entered State Science Day 2020! #AthensBulldogs

ACSD Rising 8th-12th grade #AthensBulldogs students!

This summer on Zoom we have a unique opportunity for students:

✅ This weekly group is for everyone, whatever your race or your feelings about the topic.
✅ We have a large and amazing team of facilitators, representing diversity in race, class, ethnicity, religion, sexual orientation, gender identity, age & more.
✅ We have small groups to support each other, learn together and have fun
a safe environment where we can talk openly, sharing experiences & ideas.
✅ Facilitators include: Lacey Rogers, Tammy Tucker, Laura Black, Trisha Lachman, Janai Travis, Keshawn Mellon, Allison Ricket, Chris Stepp, Brandon Thompson, Winsome Chunnu-Brayda, Rachel Siegel and John Schmieding.

Let us know if you are interested and we will try to find times that work for everyone.

Contact John Schmieding
Email: johnsch.45701@gmail.com
Text: 740-517-1978

Voice of Democracy is an annual nationwide scholarship program sponsored by the Veterans of Foreign Wars. Under the direction of their teacher, Mr. Marrs, students wrote essays for this year’s theme, “What Makes America Great?”

The Plains VFW awarded recognition to three local middle school students for their essays. Luke Rodgers was recognized as the first place winner and awarded $500. Emerson Crowl and Wynne Dodrill received honorable mention and were each awarded $250.

#AthensBulldogs

✔️ Please remain in your cars, forming a line in the parking lot.
✔️ As you arrive at the main entrance, we ask that only 2 people at a time approach the entrance, and only 1 person per vehicle.

✔️ We ask that you wear a mask, if possible.

Our team will work as fast as we can to keep the line moving so folks don't have to wait too long.

Thank you for keeping all of us safe! We look forward to seeing you!

post_text:
Help us celebrate and thank Linda Milliken as she retires from our #AthensBulldogs community. She is wrapping up her 29th year with ACSD.

𝘓𝘪𝘯𝘥𝘢'𝘴 𝘍𝘢𝘷𝘰𝘳𝘪𝘵𝘦 𝘔𝘦𝘮𝘰𝘳𝘺:
"When I look back over my teaching career my favorite memories will always be of how rewarding it's been to be able to spend my days with students. The joy that comes from watching them become readers is priceless, and that is the thing I will miss most."

𝘓𝘪𝘯𝘥𝘢'𝘴 𝘗𝘭𝘢𝘯𝘴 𝘧𝘰𝘳 𝘙𝘦𝘵𝘪𝘳𝘦𝘮𝘦𝘯𝘵:
"My plans for retirement just a few months ago are quite different than my plans for retirement now, thanks to the pandemic. It's certainly a bittersweet ending to my career to not be able to say goodbye to my students and colleagues. I do look forward to spending more time with my daughter and her family in California. I also want to do some traveling, especially to my cabin in Quebec, Canada. However, the virus will determine when I can safely do those things. So in the meantime, I'll be working in my garden and reading."

Congrats and THANK YOU, Linda, for your time and dedication to our staff, students, and families!

Congratulations to #AthensBulldogs Emerson Elliott on her nomination of the Marine Semper Fidelis All-American Battles Won Academy.

Attendees must submit a detailed account of athletic achievements, academic achievements, official transcript, volunteering and community service, as well as a 500-word essay.

The Ohio Educational Service Center Association (OESCA) recognized 84 of Ohio’s top students from across the state during the 31st Annual Franklin B. Walter All-Scholastic Awards Program.

The awards program, named in honor of Ohio’s 31st State Superintendent of Public Instruction, Franklin B. Walter, was established in 1989 by OESCA to promote and recognize outstanding student leaders for their academic achievement and service to their schools and communities. One senior from each county in Ohio was eligible to receive this annual honor. Eligible applicants must be a high school senior enrolled in a public school within an ESC’s service region. Recipients were required to demonstrate outstanding academic achievement and community service as indicated by high school grades, test scores, school and community activities and awards.

Athens High School senior, Jonathan Lee, was recognized as the recipient of the Franklin B. Walter All-Scholastic Award from Athens County.

Congratulations Jonathan! #AthensBulldogs

Several #AthensBulldogs competed virtually in the state National History Day with documentaries that they made.

Emma Hartman, an AHS freshman, recently created a documentary for the Ohio National History Day competition. Her documentary, Passion Works: Breaking Barriers with Community Art, depicts the inclusive art studio Passion Works in Athens, Ohio. Through interviews with Passion Works artists, staff, and volunteers, her documentary gives voice to unique perspectives and highlights the impact of inclusive community-based work for people with disabilities.

Here is the YouTube link to her documentary:
https://youtu.be/7aa0A6FxS4U

Check out the details: https://tinyurl.com/athenshistoryday

Did you know that May 6th is National School Nurse Day?

This year's theme – School Nurses: Supporting Students in Times of Crisis – reinforces the changing times of 2020. This year, more than ever, all members of our school communities, school nurses included, have been required to take on unprecedented roles and adapt quickly to changes in their jobs. We celebrate and honor the significant role school nurses play in the health and safety of their schools and communities during this crisis.

Learn more at: www.schoolnurseday.org

Put your 👏 together for Nurse Molly and Nurse Heidi.

We appreciate you! 💚 #AthensBulldogs

Congratulations to #AthensBulldogs Nikki Bean on her nomination of the Marine Semper Fidelis All-American Battles Won Academy. She recently received news that she was a finalist, but because of COVID along with her mentor AHS English Teacher, Allison Ricket, is not able to attend this summer for the safety of all the athletes. The Semper Fidelis All-American Program recognizes high school students who face life's battles with the conviction and the determination to succeed.

Attendees must submit a detailed account of athletic achievements and academics, official transcript, volunteering, and community service, as well as a 500 word written essay.

For more information: https://www.marines.com/2020finalistlist.html

Congratulations, Nikki! 👏👏

post_text:
It is with great honor and privilege to share that Adam Gonczy has been named a National Coach of the month! Coach Gonczy is the Track and Field coach at Athens High School. 👏👏

Coach Gonczy knew the moment the spring sports season was cancelled he wasn’t going to let this change stop him from coaching and motivating his team. He immediately figured out a way to plan a virtual track meet for his team to prepare for at home and compete to help keep his team motivated and excited. He also wanted to keep spirits high, so he has been sharing daily motivationally quotes and images with this team. He has leveraged social media to get out the word on the virtual track and meet; check it out here. Coach Gonczy has found a way to stay connected with his team and for the team to continue to compete despite school closures and season cancellations.

#AthensBulldogs

Although we are social distancing, we are still community connecting!

Today Ms. Ricket’s Sophomore English Classes were joined virtually by Ohio University Fulbright scholar Mohammed Sakhi Hassany. Mohammed gave us insight into the facts behind the book “The Kite Runner.” He shared about his life and work in Afghanistan, the realities of life under the Taliban, and the culture of his home. We are so grateful to Mohammed for joining us.

We are also grateful to Riverhead Books for providing the PDF version of “The Kite Runner” so our students could finish the year with this important book.

Athens High School 9th grader Seir Welser has been selected to receive a Congress-Bundestag Youth Exchange (CBYX) scholarship! This program, funded by the US State Department and the German government, provides intensive language training and fully funds a semester-long study abroad experience in Germany starting in January 2021.

CBYX is a highly selective and competitive program and we are proud of Seir for receiving the scholarship! Seir wants to thank AHS teachers Alison Ricket and Eric Miller for their support and mentoring through the application process.

More info about CBYX - https://usagermanyscholarship.org/about-cbyx/

#AthensBulldogs

post_text:
#AthensBulldogs families!

To help support the Athens City School District (ACSD) successfully transition to online instruction, Ohio University's Office of Information Technology (OIT) will provide tech support for ACSD students and instructors, helping the district's handful of IT employees keep up with what is likely to be a flood of support calls in the coming weeks.

Starting April 13, families within the Athens City School District may call 740-593-1223 (option #2) for help with internet setup, online learning apps, and device troubleshooting.

“We’re fortunate to have this partnership with OHIO’s OIT to help support our students and faculty in this difficult time,” Tom Gibbs, Superintendent of Athens City School District, said. “We understand the challenges for some in our community when it comes to technology and believe this support will truly help our students in remote learning.”

Calls will be fielded by OIT student employees who worked at the IT Service Desk in the Tech Depot before social distancing restrictions closed that location.

https://tinyurl.com/OUsupportBulldogs

post_text:
Attention, #AthensBulldogs families!

The Athens Bulldog Elementary X-Country Clubs Sponsor: The VIRTUAL Forget Me Not 5K Run/Walk

In memory of Patsy D. Barrington
Date: April 11, 2020
Time: 11:00 am

Due to Ohio's Stay At Home Order and restrictions on non-essential items we are changing the format of this event! We hope that you will still participate, making it your own, and running or walking a 5K within your close circle of family members! All of course, with good memories of Patsy in mind!

We want you wear something colorful, play some fun music, and run or walk a 5K on the course of your choice! If you knew Patsy, snap a selfie and post it on Patsyś Facebook wall or tag her. If not, enjoy a run or walk by intentionally putting GOOD VIBES out into the universe! Or, better yet, BOTH!

We ask that you make a donation if you are able. Half of the proceeds go to the Susan Matters and her Family. The other half will go to Kids on Campus.

For further details or information contact Liz at lschwarzel@athenscsd.org or 740.818.9469.

Join several of our #AthensBulldogs virtually as their art is displayed for all to see!

This annual exhibition at Ohio University showcasing photography by students from Southeast Ohio regional high schools was juried for the first time by Ohio University professors Laura Larson, School of Art + Design, and Gary Kirksey, School of Visual Communications.

Student work representing Alexander, Athens, Federal Hocking, Nelsonville-York, Vinton Co. and Western High Schools is featured in the 2020 exhibition.

Take a tour virtually and see if you can spot some of our students! 👏👏

ACSD donated PPE from the schools (classrooms, clinics, etc.) to the Athens County Health Department, including:

89 boxes unopened gloves
27 opened/partial boxes of gloves
10 protective apparel kits (with gowns, goggles, gloves and masks)
2 unopened gowns
5 pair goggles
6 opened/partial boxes of masks (including surgical and N95)

Thank you to the staff who made this donation possible! 💚💚

If you have any of these items to donate, please call the Health Department at 740-447-5924.

We need your help, #AthensBulldogs! For our Friday Feature, we will recognize and showcase our staff here in Athens. Help us celebrate them!

Let us show our appreciation for Irene Hancock, 9th and 11th grade English teacher at Athens High School. She has 1.5 years of experience.

Students call her: Miss Hancock/Lil Teach/Captain Hancock/Chairwoman Hancock. 😄

Miss Hancock loves helping students discover their passion and what drives them. She hopes that what she does each day helps the students gain the confidence to be the best versions of themselves while also learning how to cope with difficult emotions that come with being a teenager - and let's be honest, an adult too!

She LOVES being at Athens High School. She adores her colleagues, students, and administrators. She considers herself very lucky.

Join us in thanking Miss Hancock for all her time and energy in our school and community!

Attention, #AthensBulldogs!

It is important that parents/guardians complete this survey as quickly as possible.

We are working on a plan to begin meal deliveries on Monday, March 23rd and to begin remote instruction on March 30th. Those who can respond online, please do so as quickly as possible. For those who do not have access and have not responded online we will begin making phone contacts by Thursday morning.

Thanks for your support and help.

post_text:
It is with much appreciation that we THANK Josh and Sandi Radcliff of the Radcliff Sales Team at LCR Realty for their generous donation to our #AthensBulldogs School music programs. This year, at both the OU men and women's basketball games, anytime the opposing team missed a free throw, a donation of $10 was made to the Athens School District's music programs.

The Radcliff Sales Team presented a celebratory signed game ball at a recent O.U. Men's basketball game and will be presenting a check with a total of $1,100 to Athens City School District Superintendent, Thomas J. Gibbs, Ed.D.

We are so appreciative of your help of our students and the school community! 💚 Josh Radcliff of LCR Realty Sandi Radcliff at LCR Realty

post_text:
Emma Hartman competed in the Senior Individual Documentary Region 9 National History Day competition and won the honor of competing at the state competition on April 25th. Reynold Huard and Elena Johnson (not pictured) won the same honors in the Senior Group Division. They are pictured with their adviser, Angie Hall.

Reynolds and Elena made a documentary about breaking barriers in mental health treatment at the Athens Asylum throughout its history. Emma honored Passion Works with a beautiful documentary about breaking barriers with the use of art for the our community members with disabilities. These students worked independently to create their outstanding documentaries and were complimented by the judges for collegiate level research, writing, public speaking skills, and academic work.

#AthensBulldogs #proud

post_text:
#AthensBulldogs at The Plains Elementary have been learning about dental health. Since February is Dental Health Month, they studied how what we drink affects our teeth. 🦷🦷

They used hard-boiled eggs and placed them in milk, Coke Zero, and water for 24 hours. The shell of the egg represents our teeth. They made predictions and observed the changes.

What do you think their results were❓ The students concluded that Coke Zero was bad for their teeth!

We need your help, #AthensBulldogs! For our Friday Feature, we will recognize and showcase our staff here at Athens. Help us celebrate them!

We recognize Mrs. Milliken, Literacy Coordinator and Reading Intervention (grades K-3) at The Plains Elementary. She has 29 years of experience.

The best part of her job is the students and the wonderful colleagues she is lucky enough to spend the day with. After 29 years of teaching in the Athens City School District, she is retiring at the end of the school year. She is looking forward to many new and different adventures.

Join us in thanking Mrs. Milliken for all her time and energy in our school and community!

We need your help, #AthensBulldogs! For our Friday Feature, we will recognize and showcase our staff here at Athens.

Let us show our appreciation for Molly Roach, English teacher and yearbook advisor at Athens High School. She has 15 years of experience.

The best part of her job is when her students start to understand and love a novel that they are reading in class. She loves their class discussions and way, still after 15 years of experience, students can surprise her with new insights that she hasn't considered. She also loves when her students become so engaged in a novel that they beg to find out what happens, or to read more, or they come to class to discuss what they have read the night before.

Join us in thanking Mrs. Roach for all her time and energy in our school and community!

Attention, ACSD Families!

Please join us for a demonstration of the AHS Makerspace prior to the regular board of education meeting at 6:30 pm TONIGHT (2/20). We will begin in the auditorium at 5:45 pm and move to the Industrial Technology Lab from there.

The Athens High School Industrial Technology classes have been working hard to install the new AHS Makerspace. They painted the former paint room in the industrial arts classroom, created work benches for the machines, and assembled the workplace and machines. AHS maintenance and technology have installed power and increased the wireless capacity in the area to help ensure proper operations.

#AthensBulldogs

post_text:
We are very excited to share that on Friday, February 21, 2020, Alex Sheen has volunteered to come and speak to all of Athens County juniors and seniors.

Alex was a presenter at Prom Impact a few years ago. Since we do not have the Prom Impact event anymore, Alex contacted Judge Stewart who put him in contact with Deputy Jimmy Childs of the Athens County Sheriff Department. AHS has been working with Deputy Childs to make arrangements for the event to be held this coming Friday in the AHS gymnasium from 10:00 am - 12:00 pm. Students will have the opportunity to meet Alex after the event.

Other local high schools including Tri-County Career Center, Federal Hocking High School, Trimble High School, and Nelsonville-York High School are bringing their upperclassmen to the event.

I hope that all CC+ students feel welcome to attend even if they are not usually on campus during this time. If there are any questions, please do not hesitate to contact Mr. Springer at Athens High School.

https://becauseisaidiwould.org/alexsheen

#AthensBulldogs
